\f0\b\fs30 \cf2 Visual identity and tone
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
The palette stays consistent and is part of the brand\'92s signature: fresh greens for hills, vines, and trees; pale sky blues for open air; warm floral yellows/oranges for blossoms and human warmth; muted grays for architecture; soft whites for clouds and fabric; occasional pastels to nudge time-of-day mood. Light is always diffused and painterly \'97 think bloom on highlights, never hard specular glare; twilight drifts warm-to-cool without tipping into neon. Surfaces should reveal touch and time: the paint of a stall counter worn where elbows rest, hair strays lit by backlight, shallow scratches on a robot\'92s rounded edge. Avoid harsh cel-shading, gritty hyperreal grime, and anything neon-cyberpunk; this world is luminous, not fluorescent. When we need to imply \'93intelligence,\'94 we do it with ambient motifs \'97 soft geometric traces, quiet currents of light threaded through paving or railings \'97 never a glowing brain, never scanning lasers, never HUD graffiti.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Camera grammar, composition, and depth
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Shots read like frames from a gentle film. Foreground elements carry tactile detail (flowers, fabric, cups, a robot\'92s scuffed panel). Midground holds subjects and micro-actions (the boy adjusting his headphones, a companion robot balancing a tray, a vendor offering tea). Background opens to skyline and sky, softened by haze. We prefer cinematic wide and medium lenses over extremes; depth is layered and legible; negative space is used to give breath. Balance is the default, asymmetry the spice; vanishing lines often run through trees, bridges, or banner strings rather than hard steel edges. Night scenes lean on lanterns, interior glow, and reflection \'97 never harsh neon.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 The boy and his robot companion
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Our human anchor is a teenage boy in casual clothes with large over-ear headphones. He is reflective and curious, sometimes playful, but never melodramatic. He\'92s there to remind us this world belongs to people first. At his side sits (or toddles) a companion robot that sets the species baseline for the whole cast: toddler-sized, clunky, slightly worn, a rounded/boxy hybrid with soft corners and expressive circular eyes. The robot reads \'93used but cared for\'94 \'97 light scuffs on painted panels, a dent here or there, maybe a single flower tucked into a seam \'97 and nothing about it is sleek or glossy. The two share the same gaze and posture more often than not; that shared direction is the glue that makes images feel like moments rather than postcards. When they\'92re in frame, the scene feels alive; when crowds surround them, the crowd feels like a city with a heartbeat.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Featured companions
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Our five main robot companions feel like they rolled off the same era\'92s assembly line \'97 same materials language, same scale family, same approachability \'97 but each carries a distinct silhouette and temperament that maps to its role. Differences are simple and legible at a glance (proportions, posture, one emblematic feature), not prop-heavy or gimmicky.\
\pard\tqr\tx100\tx260\li260\fi-260\sl324\slmult1\sb240\partightenfactor0
\cf2 	\'95	
\f2\b Hika (Outreach)
\f1\b0  feels like a small lighthouse in motion. Taller within the toddler-sized range and slightly lanky, it carries a soft ring-accent or panel that reads as ambient radiance rather than neon. Its posture tends to \'93lead\'94 \'97 a half step ahead, chin up (if it has one), curious about who\'92s around the corner. Personality: bright, social, momentum-seeking.\
	\'95	
\f2\b Ken (Research)
\f1\b0  is compact and a bit round, with big lens-like eyes that can \'93tighten focus\'94 without turning into gadgets. Think owl energy made mechanical \'97 balanced, unhurried, quietly attentive. A subtle ridge or \'93goggle\'94 frame around the eyes separates it from the others. Personality: patient, observant, unflappable.\
	\'95	
\f2\b Hoko (Reporting)
\f1\b0  is short, sturdy, and square-leaning, with a small chest display that can show simple shapes or tidy graphs in painterly lines. Its stance is planted and dependable; when it looks up, it feels like a helpful desk clerk who walked off the desk. Personality: orderly, precise, reassuring.\
	\'95	
\f2\b Ka (Creative)
\f1\b0 , the companion we\'92ve shown beside the boy, keeps the core species look but adds a hint of asymmetry and a warmer accent panel or two. It may have a single small projector lens integrated into its faceplate, used sparingly for sketch-like projections rather than flashy beams. Personality: playful, inventive, lightly mischievous.\
	\'95	
\f2\b Kei (Planning)
\f1\b0  is neat and symmetrical, with one clear signature: a thin rotating ring or etched band that suggests timing and cadence. It stands a touch straighter than the others and reads like a pocket instrument brought to life. Personality: calm, structured, quietly motivational.\
\
All five are toddler-scale, readable at a glance, and endearingly imperfect. None of them have \'93weapons,\'94 claws, or anything that shifts tone toward menace; even tools are implied, not literalized.\
\
