\f0\b\fs30 \cf2 The broader robot ecology
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
The city is saturated with helpers beyond the companions, and that abundance is how we communicate the world\'92s premise without exposition. You might watch a giraffe-tall infrastructure bot adjust solar shingles on a rooftop while, on the street, knee-high courier bots ferry parcels between stalls. You might see an umbrella-holder pacing alongside a hurried commuter, a plant tender humming at balcony ferns, or a pillow-fluffer that puffs a caf\'e9 cushion the instant someone stands. The variety reads as species diversity, but nothing breaks the species language: rounded edges, approachable faces (if any), a trace of wear, and an almost comic earnestness. In city-scale frames, a natural distribution keeps scenes believable: humans carry the weight (they are the story), small helpers are the texture (the smile), medium service bots are accents (the set dressing), and large infrastructure bots recede into background scale. As a rule of thumb for busy streets: humans dominate; small helpers are frequent but not swarming; medium service bots are occasional; large bots are rare and distant. The result is whimsy without clutter.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 The Intelligence (the benevolent omnipresence)
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Under the streets, along railings, and inside walls runs a subtle, city-wide \'93Intelligence\'94 \'97 the platform\'92s soul and the world\'92s connective tissue. It is not a face and not a character; it\'92s a presence you feel in the way light is organized and decisions seem to flow. Visually, it\'92s a quiet geometry: slow-moving filaments that behave like a breeze made visible, thin motifs that occasionally pulse under glass floors, a faint coherence to how lanterns brighten in sequence as a crowd arrives. The Intelligence powers the companions, shares context between them, and gently nudges human activity toward ease. When it \'93speaks,\'94 it does so through the environment or through a companion\'92s simple display \'97 a line drawn in light, a circle that resolves, a path that clarifies. The tone is warm, assuring, and almost parental in patience. This keeps us far from ominous tropes: there is no mask in the sky, no booming voice, no omniscient surveillance vibe \'97 only an ambient kindness that makes the city feel choreographed in the best way.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Story logic and micro-actions
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Every image should be a slice of life that can be described in a sentence: the boy shares noodles on a curb while Ka tries (and fails) to hold two bowls; Hoko\'92s tiny display reflects a tidy bar chart while a vendor laughs and hands over a receipt; Ken leans toward a poster wall as if it can hear the data whispering behind the paper; Kei rotates its ring while rearranging napkins into a timeline; Hika drifts a half-step forward to greet someone just entering the plaza. Small actions create the story, and the city answers: a breeze lifts pennants; lanterns warm when conversations gather; a planter spills blossoms where a musician starts to play. \'93Soft radiance\'94 is our vocabulary for every light decision \'97 ambient glow, painterly haze, reflection \'97 never neon shine.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Settings and their emotional jobs
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Rooftops open into freedom \'97 little stages, long views, casual gatherings. Market streets carry energy \'97 moving color, friendly noise, and the comedy of small robots navigating ankles and tote bags. Parks and lakes hold memory and growth \'97 blossoms that seem to remember last season\'92s songs, benches that invite reflection, sunlight filtered through leaves onto a robot\'92s worn paint. Transit hubs tell the city\'92s tempo \'97 arrivals and departures seen through glass walls scribed with vines. Interiors soften the modern \'97 caf\'e9s where tabletops are old wood and the light is soft and shallow, libraries where the ceiling is glass and the stacks are interrupted by trees. The edge of the world is honest \'97 grayscale ruins hint at an old system that lost its heart; you can see the difference without being told.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Onboarding as narrative (RPG-like without cosplay)
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Arrival is gentler than a splash screen. The user \'93steps into\'94 the world with a brief, calm address from the Intelligence: a sentence or two written like a welcome letter rather than a directive. Role selection appears as paths that feel like lanes in a city: artist, manager, executive. There is no drill-down tree; there is a choice and then an encounter. The first encounter is a meeting with a companion aligned to the user\'92s role. An artist might meet Ka first; a manager might meet Kei; an executive might meet Hoko or Hika depending on objective. The first quest is always metaphorical, never transactional: an artist \'93plants a first song seed\'94 in a quiet park; a manager \'93sets the house lights\'94 so their team can see the stage; an executive \'93opens the doors\'94 of a creative hub so the roster can gather. Under the hood, these acts wire accounts, create spaces, connect data, and spin up automations \'97 but the user experiences a short story that invites them to continue.\
\
As they progress, companions \'93call\'94 on one another. Kei might request Hika\'92s help to warm an audience. Ken might surface something Hoko should summarize. The user\'92s team grows horizontally, not up a hierarchy. A higher-level view emerges organically as the Intelligence orchestrates the companions\'92 interplay; this never feels like management layers \'97 it feels like a jazz combo getting tighter.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 The five buckets as living roles
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Outreach, research, reporting, creative, and planning map cleanly to Hika, Ken, Hoko, Ka, and Kei. Each one can perform multiple workflows without needing a new named bot for every variant. This keeps the experience legible: fewer core companions, more depth in what each can do, and the feeling of learning personalities rather than scrolling a catalog. If the product surfaces templates, we frame them as \'93tricks\'94 each companion knows \'97 a booklet of moves rather than a wall of separate agents.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Rules that prevent drift (visual and narrative)
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Humans first. Every image includes people doing something even when the setting is heroic, otherwise the city goes dead. Companions never overshadow their humans; their height, posture, and gaze keep them supportive, not starring. The species language holds: rounded edges, friendly faces, light wear, small signatures for each named companion. The palette holds: fresh greens, pale blues, warm florals, soft whites, muted grays; accents stay pastel, not neon. Light holds: bloom, haze, reflection; never HDR glare. \'93Intelligence\'94 is drawn in the margins \'97 little harmonies in how the city reacts \'97 never a deity on a screen.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Humor, delight, and abundance
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
The world is charming because it is slightly over-equipped. There\'92s a sock-matcher hunting for a partner under a caf\'e9 bench; a plant whisperer humming to balcony herbs; an umbrella-holder pacing like a loyal giraffe; a pillow-fluffer that puffs the cushion the instant you stand; a bedtime storyteller for adults who need a kinder night. These moments are not gags; they are proofs that the city values human comfort and whimsy. Large bots keep that same humility: a bridge-tender leans to nudge lantern ropes into symmetry; a solar-shingle adjuster pauses so birds can pass.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Copy and language
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
When the Intelligence speaks, sentences are short, warm, and non-directive. \'93Welcome. You brought the weather with you.\'94 \'93Let\'92s open the doors.\'94 \'93I\'92ll keep time; you keep pace.\'94 Companions speak like people who know their craft; they never quip like mascots. The boy rarely speaks aloud; his body language is the line \'97 adjusting headphones, leaning toward a friend, sitting shoulder-to-shoulder with Ka on a hill when the city needs to exhale.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 UI overlays and brand alignment
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
When type appears in-scene (posters, title cards, gentle captions), it should harmonize with your brand fonts: Plus Jakarta Sans for confident headers, Inter (or Inter Tight) for body copy that reads as modern and humane. Placement is low-contrast and respectful of image balance \'97 bottom-left, top-right, or along a natural line in the scene. Numbers and charts, when Hoko shows them, are sketched with painterly restraint; they feel like notes in a field journal, not a dashboard glued to a painting.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 Practical art direction notes (to keep teams aligned)
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Robots are toddler-height against seated humans and knee-to-waist against standing humans. Wear level is \'93lightly used\'94 \'97 one or two notable dings and a general patina, never grime. Faces, hands, and robot eyes carry the sharpest detail; backgrounds soften with distance. Crowd density is human-weighted; robot variety is present but never swarms. Market scenes prefer fabric banners and wooden counters to seas of plastic. Rain scenes are reflection-driven (watercolor streets) rather than soaked clothing drama. Night is lantern and windowlight; day is cloud-soft and scattered. If an image feels empty, add a micro-action (someone handing something, a robot trying, failing, and trying again) before you add an object.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 How the Intelligence relates to companions and users
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
Think of the Intelligence as the conductor and the companions as musicians who can both solo and play ensemble. The user is the bandleader whose taste sets direction. The Intelligence keeps tempo and remembers the tune; companions translate intent into action. Power feels centralized but never authoritarian; guidance is constant but never intrusive. The visual cue for this relationship is coordination \'97 how lights queue when a group gathers, how doors open in rhythm with footsteps, how a companion \'93knows\'94 where to be without being told.\
\

\f0\b\fs30 First quests that set tone without breaking immersion
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
An artist begins by \'93planting a seed\'94 in a small garden square; under the hood this uploads a song, writes metadata, and drafts a share. A manager \'93sets the house lights,\'94 which actually wires their workspace, invites collaborators, and connects calendars. An executive \'93opens the doors,\'94 which spins up a roster space, connects catalogs, and assigns companions. The user never sees a task checklist first; they see an action with meaning. The more they do these acts, the more the city seems to know them \'97 benches where they pause feel familiar, stalls greet them with the right tools, and companions anticipate the next move.\
